feet of vertical clearance, doubling the station's range from 30 to 60 miles. A swimming pool with diving board was installed at the entrance for aquatic telecasts. The ridge is still named Mount Lee — the permanent legacy of a 9th-generation Hooker descendant above one of the most recognized landmarks in America.","body":"The ridge above the Hollywood sign in Los Angeles is named \"Mount Lee\" after Don Lee, who established his TV transmitter there in 1941.","number":1},{"header":"Television pioneer: W6XAO → KCBS-TV","detail":"Don Lee was granted an FCC license for experimental television in 1931, beginning broadcasts of W6XAO six days a week. Engineer Harry Lubcke directed the operation; in 1932 he made history by transmitting a moving image to a receiver aboard an airplane 3,000 feet over Burbank. The station became KTSL, then KNXT, and is now KCBS-TV — the CBS flagship station for the West Coast.","body":"Granted the first LA television license in 1931; his station became KCBS-TV, the CBS West Coast flagship still broadcasting today.","number":2},{"header":"Harley Earl — the GM designer Don Lee launched","detail":"In 1919 Don Lee purchased the Earl Automobile Works of Hollywood and renamed it Don Lee Coach and Body Works. He retained young Harley Earl as manager. The shop produced many custom Cadillacs for Hollywood celebrities. In 1927 Harley Earl left to become the first head of the General Motors Art and Color Section (later Styling), where he went on to design the Corvette and revolutionize American automotive aesthetics — a career launched under a Hooker descendant's roof.","body":"Purchased the Earl Automobile Works in 1919 and kept Harley Earl as manager; Earl left in 1927 to become head of GM's styling department, shaping American car design for decades.","number":3}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Donald Musgrave Lee","first_name":"Donald","last_name":"Lee","middle_name":"Musgrave","married_names":[]},"residence":{